[[File:Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant.jpg|thumb|[[Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant]] in [[Guangdong]] supplying electricity to [[Hong Kong]] since 1994]] [[File:Yangjiang NPP 2009-1.jpg|thumb|[[Yangjiang Nuclear Power Station]] in [[Guangdong]] will supply electricity to Hong Kong in 2017]]
Currently, there is no '''nuclear power plant in Hong Kong'''. However, a [[Hong Kong]] company, [[Hong Kong Nuclear Investment Company]] (HKNIC), owns 25% share in [[Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant]] in [[Guangdong]]. About 70% of the power plant electricity output is supplied to Hong Kong by their electric utility company [[CLP Group|China Light and Power Co., Ltd.]] (CLP) to meet the electricity demand in Hong Kong.<ref name="legco">{{cite web|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr10-11/english/panels/se/papers/se0117cb2-767-2-e.pdf|date=11 January 2011|publisher=立法會Legislative Council|title=Background brief prepared by the Legislative Council Secretariat for the special meeting on 17 January 2011 &#124; Daya Bay Nuclear Power Station Notification Mechanism|accessdate=2014-08-23}}</ref>
==Electricity import from nuclear power plants in Mainland China== Hong Kong currently imports electricity from [[Mainland China]] from the [[Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant]] in [[Guangdong]] since 1994. The agreement of electricity import lasts until 2034. [[CLP Group|CLP]] will also import 17% of electricity from the planned [[Yangjiang Nuclear Power Station]] in Guangdong by 2017 under the agreement with [[China Guangdong Nuclear Power Company]].
==Carbon emission mitigation== To reduce the carbon dioxide emission in Hong Kong, new coal-fired power plants have not been allowed to be built anymore since 1997. The [[government of Hong Kong]] have been trying to boost the share of [[renewable energy]], natural gas and [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]] for power generation in Hong Kong. The current existing coal-fired power plants will be kept on low utilization as [[power reserve|reserve]].
The government itself plan to cut carbon emission up to 50-60% from the current emission by 2020 by gradually replacing coal-based power generation with more nuclear power and other [[Sustainable energy|green energy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/EE_Hong_Kong_to_replace_coal_with_nuclear_1509101.html |title=Hong Kong to replace coal with nuclear |publisher= [[World-nuclear-news.org]] |date=2010-09-15 |accessdate=2014-04-21}}</ref>
